		<div class="story-heads">
		<h1>For Women’s History Month, A Reproductive Rights Reading List</h1>
		<h2>Clara Bingham Recommends Irin Carmon, Muriel Fox, Stephanie Gorton and More</h2>	</div>
	<div class="sponsored"><a href="https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Movement/Clara-Bingham/9781982144227" target="_blank" class="external">Via Atria/One Signal Publishers</a></div></div>
										<div class="byline-date">
					<span class="byline"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/clara-bingham/"  title="Clara Bingham">Clara Bingham</a></span>
					<span class="hr"></span>
					<span class="date">March 20, 2026</span>
				</div>
						<div class="story-body">
								<p>Women’s History Month lands this year smack in the middle of the biggest antifeminist backlash since Norman Mailer insulted Germaine Greer on the stage at <a href="https://phfilms.com/films/town-bloody-hall/" class="external" target="_blank">Town Hall</a> in 1971. The literary grandfather of the “manosphere,” Mailer bellowed the ideas finding traction in today’s pronatalist movement—keep women at home, pregnant, and preferably as sexy as possible. We can assume that Mailer would be just as dismissive of the gold medal winning Olympic women’s hockey team as our president. Another backlash player is the Tradwife movement with its viral vibe of birthing lots of babies with no pain killers, making bread from scratch, and selling homespun merch on Instagram. But this has the feel of a trend that has come, and inevitably will go.</p>
<p>Nestled like a malignant tumor alongside these life choice women’s rights regressions lies a true life-and-death crisis facing women today—abortion bans. Ever since the Supreme Court reversed <i>Roe v. Wade</i> in 2022, <a href="https://www.kff.org/womens-health-policy/exceptions-in-state-abortion-bans-and-early-gestational-limits/" class="external" target="_blank">19 states</a> have completely or nearly banned abortion, creating a legal framework that instantly rendered life-threatening the level of reproductive healthcare care available to <a href="https://www.plannedparenthoodaction.org/uploads/filer_public/85/e8/85e8c25c-1c53-41c6-b26f-aff322519f9d/0624-c4_c3-bans-off-state-pop-data-pdf-v7.pdf" class="external" target="_blank">43-percent</a> of women of childbearing age in this country.</p>
<p>In that vein, here are eleven books that I recommend reading this month. They were published on or after 2024, and most, but not all, cover different aspects of the reproductive rights wars. I have listed them alphabetically by author’s last names.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="268250" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/for-womens-history-month-a-reproductive-rights-reading-list/unbearable/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable.jpg" data-orig-size="795,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="unbearable" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable-678x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-268250" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable-199x300.jpg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/unbearable.jpg 795w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668032602" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Unbearable: Five Women and the Perils of Pregnancy in America</i></a> by Irin Carmon</strong></p>
<p>In her exploration of what it takes to give birth in America today, <i>New York</i> magazine writer and co-author of <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780062415837" class="external" target="_blank"><i>The Notorious RBG</i></a>, tells the intimate story of five pregnant women who live in different states, and the struggles they endure (some worse than others depending on socioeconomics and geography) to navigate often dangerous and inhumane reproductive care system.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="268251" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/for-womens-history-month-a-reproductive-rights-reading-list/the-fall-of-roe/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe.jpg" data-orig-size="789,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="the fall of roe" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe-673x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-268251" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe-197x300.jpg" alt="" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe-673x1024.jpg 673w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe-768x1168.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-fall-of-roe.jpg 789w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250881427" class="external" target="_blank"><i>The Fall of Roe: The Rise of a New America</i></a><i> </i>by Elizabeth Dias and Lisa Lerer</strong></p>
<p>Two tenacious <em>New York Times</em> investigative reporters chronicle the inside story of the decades-long legal and political strategy conservative Christian lawyers and lobbyists devised to reverse 49 years of abortion-rights precedent. This is the seminal “who dun it” behind the Supreme Court’s reversal of <i>Roe v. Wade.</i></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="268252" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/for-womens-history-month-a-reproductive-rights-reading-list/the-womens-revolution/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-womens-revolution.jpg" data-orig-size="677,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="the womens revolution" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-womens-revolution-203x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-womens-revolution.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-268252" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-womens-revolution-203x300.jpg" alt="" width="203" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-womens-revolution-203x300.jpg 203w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-womens-revolution-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-womens-revolution-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/the-womens-revolution.jpg 677w" sizes="(max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781613322444" class="external" target="_blank"><i>The Women’s Revolution: How We Changed Your Life</i></a><i> </i>by Muriel Fox</strong></p>
<p>A rare first-hand account of the formation of the National Organization for Women (NOW) in 1966 and its evolution over the next two decades by one of the last living founders of NOW. Muriel Fox was an insider who knew all of the players, and her candid descriptions of the events and personalities that made history (yes, Betty Friedan was a monster, but a brilliant one) makes for a dramatic story.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="268253" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/for-womens-history-month-a-reproductive-rights-reading-list/icon-and-idealist/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist.jpg" data-orig-size="795,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="icon and idealist" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist-678x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-268253" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist-199x300.jpg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/icon-and-idealist.jpg 795w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063036291" class="external" target="_blank"><i>The Icon &amp; The Idealist: Margaret Sanger, Mary Ware Dennett, and the Rivalry that Brought Birth Control to America</i></a> by Stephanie Gorton</strong></p>
<p>A gripping double biography of the two foremothers of the American birth control movement. Gorton skillfully depicts the grueling decades-long struggle of Sanger (the icon, in this telling) and Dennett (the idealist) to make birth control available and legal, as well as their interpersonal competition for power and influence.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="268254" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/for-womens-history-month-a-reproductive-rights-reading-list/access/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access.jpg" data-orig-size="795,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="access" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access-678x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-268254" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access-199x300.jpg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/access.jpg 795w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668053249" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Access: Inside the Abortion Underground and the Sixty-Year Battle for Reproductive Freedom</i></a> by Rebecca Grant </strong></p>
<p>A sweeping history of abortion in America and the development of the abortion drug mifepristone and the heroic underground efforts in Argentina, Mexico, Ireland, and ultimately America to get it into the hands of women in need.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="267692" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/murder-at-the-supreme-court-who-really-killed-roe-v-wade/killers-of-roe/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1696,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Killers of Roe" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-678x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-267692" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-199x300.jpg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-1017x1536.jpg 1017w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-1356x2048.jpg 1356w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Killers-of-Roe-scaled.jpg 1696w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781538769041" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Killers of Roe: My Investigation into the Mysterious Death of Abortion Rights</i></a><i> </i>by Amy Littlefield</strong></p>
<p>Getting to the bottom of why we lost <i>Roe</i>, is Littlefield’s mission in this important and suspenseful book. Littlefield, a veteran reporter, travels the country interviewing the religious grass roots organizers—many of whom are lost to history—who dedicated their lives to successfully dismantling reproductive rights for women.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="245120" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/that-kind-of-woman-on-motherhood-as-a-choice-not-a-destiny/a-termination/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/a-termination.jpg" data-orig-size="700,1079" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="a termination" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/a-termination-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/a-termination-664x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-245120" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/a-termination-195x300.jpg" alt="" width="195" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/a-termination-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/a-termination-664x1024.jpg 664w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/a-termination-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/a-termination-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/a-termination.jpg 700w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 195px) 100vw, 195px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798985976922" class="external" target="_blank"><i>A Termination</i></a> by Honor Moore</strong></p>
<p>A searingly intimate, lyrically written memoir chronically Moore’s abortion in 1969 at the age of 23. The celebrated poet and memoirist, delves into the agonies of her decision and describes the emerging women’s liberation movement, of which Moore would soon become a participant.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="268255" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/for-womens-history-month-a-reproductive-rights-reading-list/winning-the-earthquake/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake.jpg" data-orig-size="789,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="winning the earthquake" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake-673x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-268255" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake-197x300.jpg" alt="" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake-673x1024.jpg 673w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake-768x1168.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/winning-the-earthquake.jpg 789w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250353047" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Winning the Earthquake: How Jeannette Rankin Defied All Odds to Become the First Woman in Congress</i></a> by Lorissa Rinehart</strong></p>
<p>The first full biography of the first woman elected to Congress, Jeannette Rankin’s life spanned most of the 20th Century’s big events—the long campaign for women’s suffrage, three major wars, and the second wave feminist movement. Rankin’s life-long commitment to social justice and equality is an inspiration especially in this time when politicians who speak their minds are few and far between.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="268256" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/for-womens-history-month-a-reproductive-rights-reading-list/liberating-abortion/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/liberating-abortion.png" data-orig-size="664,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="liberating abortion" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/liberating-abortion-199x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/liberating-abortion.png" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-268256" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/liberating-abortion-199x300.png" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/liberating-abortion-199x300.png 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/liberating-abortion-40x60.png 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/liberating-abortion-33x50.png 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/liberating-abortion.png 664w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063228245" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Liberating Abortion: Claiming Our History, Sharing Our Stories, and Building the Reproductive Future We Deserve</i></a><i> </i>by Renee Bracey Sherman and Regina Mahone</strong></p>
<p>A much needed take on abortion history, activism, and lived experience for women of color, whose significant roles are often erased from history. Sherman and Mahone interview dozens of Black and Brown women who were on the front lines of the abortion battles many years before <i>Roe</i>. Their interviews with two Black women members of the underground Abortion Counseling Service in Chicago—code named Jane—is particularly interesting.</p>
